freetext_feedback_3mo_t: i learned some new techniques, and got better about regularly practicing kegels and the variations.   On the plus side, I thought all the info provided was clear, and as far as I understand, it was correct and should be helpful.  I feel like a lot of thought went into making all the information clear. It was presented in a way that was non-shaming. Those with issues are treated with respect and compassion and encouraged to advocate clearly for their needs. I  applaud you for all this,  these are clearly needed in this discussion.     But I'd ask you to reconsider the title of your Program to reflect greater inclusivity and an understanding that sex and gender aren't always the same. Many trans men, for example, also have this problem.    I was not a fan of the booklet that was sent.  It had room for all the pertinent info, but it reall had a middle-school project vibe about it all. Very repetitive, and plenty of thought went into making it easy, but nothing about it seemed fun. Nothing about it was attractive.  Nothing wanted to make me linger over it. It felt immature and boring, to be honest.  And so big!  I didn't want to bring it out while traveling, nothing discreet about it.   I can envision something half the size and more attractive. Even if still b&w, it could be a nicer font, etc.     I'd also like to suggest that you enlist the help of some digital design and gamer undergrads at UW-Madison to help re-imagine your app. To me it seems very little like an app, it really is just like a website with some informative videos. And I'm sorry, but they were boring and appeared to be produced as inexpensively as possible. The woman with the zipper and the hoodie? In 2024, that is just so behind the times.  How about an animation that illustrates the actual physical procress we are trying to recreate in ourselves? The zipper analogy is good, or an elevator... can the video be livelier, though?    I  think that with some creative energy going toward making the app more user friendly and interactive, it would be far more helpful!  How about give users the option of a digital goal- and progress-tracker, or the paper booklet?  An on-line progress tracker could include the option for regular prompts through the day, it could offer encouragement and suggestions , and congratulations when goals are met. It could be colorful and vibrant!    You could also have a no-nonsense digital mode for people who prefer that sort of thing.      I can imagine an app could include songs that are helpful for counting along on some of these exercises.  I have a hard time staying motivated sometimes and I think some songs could be helpful.  Maybe other bells and whistles,  stuff like videos that count along with you. Maybe some count-along videos that help you stay on track. I really am not up on all the latest digital innovations, but I think something could be created that is fun and motivational while still be informative and respectful.
